Automating Data Cleansing¶

  1. dropping any NA values
  2. dropping columns not usable for analysis
  3. finding which columns may have missing values
  4. removing missing values
  5. converting categorical variables to continuous where applicable
  6. checking the categories and their counts for each variable
In [13]:
print('Dropping all NA values\n')
df.dropna(inplace=True)
for i in df.columns:
    if len(df[i].unique()) ==len(df) and type(df[i][92])==str:
        print(f'Dropping the column {i}, as it cannot add value in analysis because of all unique values\n')
        df = df.drop(i, axis = 1)
    
    else:
        for j in df[i].unique():
            if j==' ' or j=='?':
                print (i,'has missing values','\n')
                print (f'Removing missing values in {i}','\n')
                df = df[df[i]!= j]
        try:
            float(df[i][115])
            float_number = True
            if type(df[i][110])!=str:
                print(i, 'is a continuous variable\n')
            else:
                print(i, 'is a continuous variable but marked as categorical\n')
                print(f'Converting {i} to a continuous variable type\n')
                df[i] = df[i].astype(float)
        except:
            print(i,'is not a continuous variable\n')
        print(i,'\n')
        print(df[i].value_counts())
        print('\n')

In [18]:
## Testing the hypothesis that Churn is independent of gender with chi-square test
## Null Hypothesis is that Churn is similar for both males and females therefore Churn is independent of gender

chisquare([26.20,26.96], f_exp = [26.58,26.58])
Out[18]:
Power_divergenceResult(statistic=0.010865312264860844, pvalue=0.9169814240314739)
Since p value > 0.05 therefore we fail to reject the Null Hypothesis¶
Therefore we conclude on the basis of the plots, percentage of Churn for each gender and Chi-Square Test that Churn is independent of gender¶

## Testing the hypothesis that Churn is independent of whether a subscriber is a senior citizen or not with chi-square test
## Null Hypothesis is that Churn is independent of whether a subscriber is a senior citizen or not

chisquare([41.68,23.65], f_exp = [26.58,26.58])
Out[22]:
Power_divergenceResult(statistic=8.901237772761476, pvalue=0.002849774164006351)
Since p value < 0.05 therefore we reject the null hypothesis that Churn is independent of whether a subscriber is a senior citizen or not. We clearly see that if a subscriber is a senior citizen he/she is more likely to churn than others.¶

In [34]:
## We see that people who churned have a lower average tenure. We can confirm this with an ANOVA test
## NULL Hypothesis is that the average tenure for people who churn and those----
## ----who do not is the same (difference is not statistically significant)

mod = ols('tenure ~ Churn', data = df).fit()
aov_table = sm.stats.anova_lm(mod, typ = 2)
print(aov_table)

                sum_sq      df            F         PR(>F)
Churn     5.309822e+05     1.0  1007.509431  9.437650e-207
Residual  3.704983e+06  7030.0          NaN            NaN
Since p value <0.05 we reject the null hypothesis. We see that people who have churned have lower tenure on average.¶

Therefore we conclude on the basis of the plots, percentage of Churn for subscribers with and without multiple lines and Chi-Square Test that Churn is independent of whether a subscriber has multiple lines or not.¶

mod = ols('MonthlyCharges ~ Churn', data = df).fit()

                sum_sq      df          F        PR(>F)

Residual  3.468942e+10  7030.0         NaN           NaN
Since p value is < 0.05 we reject the Null Hypothesis. We see that people who churned on an average had lower total charges¶

## Creating the paramater grid for RandomizedSearch CV for Random Forest

from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV



# Number of trees in random forest
n_estimators = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(start = 200, stop = 2000, num = 19)]

# Number of features to consider at every split
max_features = ['auto', 'sqrt']

# Maximum number of levels in tree
max_depth = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(10, 100, num = 10)]
max_depth.append(None)

# Minimum number of samples required to split a node
min_samples_split = [2, 5, 10]

# Minimum number of samples required at each leaf node
min_samples_leaf = [1, 2, 4]

# Method of selecting samples for training each tree
bootstrap = [True, False]

# Create the random grid
random_grid = {'n_estimators': n_estimators,
               'max_features': max_features,
               'max_depth': max_depth,
               'min_samples_split': min_samples_split,
               'min_samples_leaf': min_samples_leaf,
               'bootstrap': bootstrap}
print(random_grid)

Using Stacking Ensemble with different Classifiers¶
In [160]:
##Creating a set of level 0 classifiers followed by a random forest classifier as the final estimator 

from sklearn.ensemble import StackingClassifier
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.naive_bayes import GaussianNB


level0 = list()
level0.append(('lr', LogisticRegression()))
level0.append(('knn', KNeighborsClassifier()))
level0.append(('cart', DecisionTreeClassifier()))
level0.append(('svm', SVC()))
level0.append(('bayes', GaussianNB()))
level0.append(('random_forest', RandomForestClassifier()))
level0.append(('Bagging', BaggingClassifier()))
level0.append(('Adboost', AdaBoostClassifier()))
level0.append(('gradient_boost', GradientBoostingClassifier()))
level0.append(('XGB', XGBClassifier()))

# define meta learner model
level1 = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)
# define the stacking ensemble
model_stack = StackingClassifier(estimators=level0, final_estimator=level1, cv=5)
# fit the model on all available data

Conclusion and Improvisation¶

In conclusion we can say that the Ensemble Techniques are quite powerful and especially the Random Forest , XGBoost and Stacking Ensemble Techniques.¶

I had built models like Logistic regression, Support Vector, Naive Bayes and KNN but none of them came close to the accuracy we got with the Ensemble Techniques.

However, an observation that I had was that the tuning of Ensemble Techniques is quite compute intensive and in terms of the value addition with respect to accuracy it is not as much. Therefore it is important to do a cost benefit analysis before hyperparameter tuning for Ensemble Techiniques.

Another observation was that even among ensemble techniques, Stacking can be very useful.

¶
From a perspective of data collection the Telecom operator could:¶
  1. Try and improve data quality in terms of missing data
  2. Try and get more data, data for just 7043 subscribers is quite low for a telecom operator
  3. Try and get more relevant features such as internet(data) usage, phone usage, Closed group networks, prepaid/postpaid etc.
  4. There is no observation on Variety and Velocity of data as the data is just one kind - tabular and is static
  5. There is no way to test the veracity of the data
